Why did Arnold do pulldowns like this? A lot of people will now claim that this is poor technique. He's actually doing it for a very good reason. A normal lat pulldown is lighter at the top and much heavier at the bottom. But your lat muscles are much stronger when they're stretched and much weaker when they're shortened. So this may present the problem, which is that your muscles are stronger where the resistance is lighter, and your muscles are weaker where the resistance is heavier. You can circumment this using the technique that Arnold's using. What he's doing is he's actually allowing the way to accelerate upward toward the stretch position, which makes these tissues, proportionately have to work much harder on the top. Then what he's doing is he's yanking out of the top portion of the range so that the momentum of the bar actually makes a little bit lighter in the bottom proportionately. Arnold is making the motion heavier at the top, where the muscles are stronger, and proportionately lighter at the bottom, where the muscles are weaker. Keep in mind that I wouldn't advise that everyone use the strategy. It's a relatively more advanced technique that you need to be able to utilize still with some degree of control.
video_description: The takeaway: cable pulling motions are generally most challenging toward the “squeezed” position. But, you’re much stronger toward the stretch, so it can make sense to initiate with a little bit of a “yank” to make the motion harder where you’re stronger. Many jacked people use this technique, which I think leaves a clue about its potential usefulness. This technique is NOT for everyone all the time. It’s a more advanced technique to perform well, and I wouldn’t advise anyone who couldn’t execute a controlled pull-down to learn them this way. But the notion that this is a “poor technique” with no reference to a goal is short-sighted (in my opinion!) and we shouldn’t write off these strategies solely as “ego lifting”. Can people take this to an extreme where little of the motion is controlled? Yes, but that doesn’t mean it can’t be done in a more balanced and intentional way.  From a practical recommendation standpoint: I do about half of my cable pulling motions with more of an intent to “yank” to challenge the stretched position and half of my pulling motions with a slower and controlled tempo to challenge the “squeeze”. Using both strategies seems reasonable to me to challenge both kinds of qualities.

How long to rest in between your sets?
voice_to_text: If you're somebody who lifts weights, how long should you be resting in between your sets? It depends on if your goal is more cardio and endurance, build muscle and get stronger, or to lose fat. For cardio and endurance training, you're usually going to have shorter rest times, somewhere around 30 to 60 seconds. Now, if your goal is to build muscle and get stronger, the current research that we have shows us is gonna be somewhere around that two to five minute Mark. This is because if you rest for too short in between your sets, you're gonna go into your next set too fatigue, which means you won't be able to lift as heavy, push yourself as close to failure, and your results are going to suffer. And by the way, if you don't need at least two minutes of rest, then that is your sign that you need to lift heavier weight. And finally, if your goal is to lose fat, you actually want your workouts focused on getting stronger in building muscle. Because combined with eating in a calorie deficit, building more muscle will help in your fat loss journey.

Why don't I recommend you run for fat loss? This is a great question, especially considering I am a runner. I've done a Marathon and an ultra Marathon, and I run three or four times a week, but I don't run for fat loss or for additional steps. The reason I don't recommend running solely for the purpose of getting more steps or losing more body fat is its effect on our appetite. Running is very glycolitic, meaning it will empty out our glycogen stores, or our stored carbohydrate. This is going to ramp up your body's appetite in the attempt to replenish those carbohydrates. While walking has a neutral impact on appetite, it does not require nearly as much energy or glycogen, so it's not gonna give you that ravenous hunger feeling. I and many others can attest to the fact that if you run a lot, you are simply hungrier. So sure, you can use running to get 10,000 steps more quickly, or even get more steps in a given day because you're covering more ground more quickly, but you need to account for the fact that you will be hungrier there by making your calorie deficit harder to stick to. All steps count. It doesn't matter if you get them running, crawling, on all fours, walking, or sprinting. Just be aware of the methods and modalities that you can get those steps and how they're gonna impact your ability to adhere to your calorie goals and needs. It isn't easy, but it is simple. Don't ever complicate it.

It’s all about the ratio of stimulus to fatigue. At a certain point you’re creating tons of “fatigue” for literally no extra stimulus, if not diminishing returns.  This point occurs much sooner than most people think.

If you want to maximize your muscle growth, you should follow these 4 rules. First, when you work out, don't seek to get a burn or make it your goal to get a pump. These will not build muscle in and of themselves. Instead, here's what your 2 goals should be. First, the best reps. Don't prioritize high rep sets because on any set taken to failure, only the last 5 stimulate growth. These other weren't doing it. Therefore, lift heavier and reach those final 5 musclebuilding reps sooner. Since you're doing fewer reps, your workout will fatigue less while stimulating the same amount of growth. Next, the perfect amount of rest between sets. You must understand you're not just waiting for your muscles to recover, it's your CNS. It's what sends this out to push your muscles hard enough. Inadequate rest, inadequate signals, less than ideal growth stimulus. After you push your hardest, it'll take your CNS about 3 minutes to recover. Here's what I do for each type of exercise multi joint upper body movements 3 to 4 minutes, upper body isolation 2 to 3 minutes, multi joint lower body movement 3 to 5 minutes, and lower body isolation usually 3 minutes. Finally, keep your methods and exercises consistent each week and get stronger at them.
